{
  "texts": [
    "If V ⊂ W is an inclusion of finite subsets of Z 2 then there is a natural embedding A V ↩→ A W by tensoring with the identity of A W \\V.",
    "For any, possibly infinite, X ⊂ Z 2 these inclusions make {A V } V ⊂⊂X into a directed system of matrix algebras.We denote its direct limit by A loc X and put AX = A loc X ∥•∥.",
    "The *-algebra A loc X is called the algebra of local observables on X, and the C * -algebra A X is called the quasi-local algebra on X.",
    "We also write A = A Z 2 and A loc = A loc Z 2, called the quasi local algebra and the local algebra respectively.For any S ⊂ R 2 let S = S ∩ Z 2 and write A S:= A S. If S is finite, we also write H S:= H S. The Levin-Wen HamiltonianLet e 1 = (1, 0) and e 2 = (0, 1) be unit vectors in Z 2 ⊂ R 2.",
    "We denote by ⃗ E = {(v 0, v 1) ∈ Z 2 × Z 2: dist(v 0, v 1) = 1} the set of oriented edges of Z 2 and by E = {(v 0, v 1) ∈ Z 2 × Z 2: v 1 -v 0 ∈ {e 1, e 2 }} the set of edges of Z 2 that are oriented to the top right."
  ]
